The same is true in the business of books. And since writing my CIA memoir =
[Shadow Cell](https://geni.us/ShadowCellBook) my mind has been BLOWN by all=
 the ways people cheat the system to have their books listed as =E2=80=98be=
stsellers=E2=80=99.

In the literary world you have two versions of bestseller lists: Editorial =
Picks vs. Statistical Picks.

Editorial picks are subjectively chosen by a group of editors who all agree=
 that one another are equally expertly adept and recognizing literary great=
ness. To put it simply, it is a good ol=E2=80=99 boys club (or even a good =
ol=E2=80=99 gals club).

Statistical picks are exactly the opposite =E2=80=93 chosen exclusively by =
sales numbers. Lots of sales means it=E2=80=99s a bestselling book.

Cheaters beat both systems in two different ways, resulting in a hybrid sys=
tem that still doesn=E2=80=99t really work=E2=80=A6

Beating editorial picks was all about playing on popular culture, especiall=
y pop-liberal culture. Not surprisingly, liberal politics and ideals domina=
te in the literary community just like they do in higher education. So if y=
ou were a minority with a pop-liberal topic that was connected with a left-=
